---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const metadata = {
  title: "General Terms and Conditions",
};
---

<BaseLayout {metadata}>
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 py-16 text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed space-y-10">

    <!-- Title -->
    <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-extrabold text-foreground">
      General Terms and Conditions
    </h1>

    <!-- Section 1 -->
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6">1. General</h2>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          These terms and conditions apply to all contracts with MBT Mechatronic Bot Technologies GmbH, Dieselstraße 11, 85757 Karlsfeld, 
          (hereinafter referred to as ‘MBT’) concerning the creation of software and the purchase of products. For better readability, 
          the word ‘customer’ refers to male, female and diverse groups of persons as well as companies.
        </li>
        <li>
          The GTC only apply if the Customer is an entrepreneur (§ 14 BGB), a legal entity under public law or a special fund under public law.
        </li>
        <li>
          The business relations between MBT and the Customer are subject to the law of the Federal Republic of Germany. The application of UN 
          sales law is excluded.
        </li>
        <li>
          Agreements made with the Customer in individual cases (including collateral agreements, supplements and amendments) shall in all cases 
          take precedence over these Terms and Conditions.
        </li>
        <li>
          The place of jurisdiction is the registered office of MBT if the Customer is a merchant, a legal entity under public law or a special 
          fund under public law. The same applies if a customer does not have a general place of jurisdiction in Germany or if the place of 
          residence or habitual abode is unknown at the time the action is brought.
        </li>
        <li>
          Attachments referenced in the order for software development or in contracts for the purchase of goods shall become part of the contract.
        </li>
        <li>
          General terms and conditions of the customer shall not apply.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <!-- Section 2 -->
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6">
        2. Conditions for Software Development Contracts
      </h2>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-2">2.1 Commencement of Software Development Contracts</h3>
      <p>
        Contracts for the development of software, the associated user documentation and the granting of rights of use enter into force on the 
        date on which the Customer accepts MBT’s offer to conclude a contract for the development of software (hereinafter referred to as the ‘Order’).
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-2">2.2 Subject Matter</h3>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          The subject matter of the software development contracts is the successful development of software by MBT and - if commissioned - the creation 
          of corresponding user documentation (hereinafter referred to collectively as ‘development results’), the transfer of these development results 
          and the granting of permanent rights of use to them.
        </li>
        <li>
          Services not expressly agreed in the order are not part of the subject matter of the contract. In particular, MBT is only obliged to maintain 
          or further develop the software to be created if MBT has been expressly commissioned to do so. The statutory warranty rights to which the 
          Customer is entitled remain unaffected by this.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-2">2.3 Subject Matter and Scope of the Development Result</h3>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          MBT will produce the development results in accordance with the order and make them available to the Customer on the date specified in the 
          order (hereinafter referred to as the ‘performance date’) - if agreed, in a test environment for provisional acceptance, otherwise for final 
          acceptance.
        </li>
        <li>
          The customer shall accept the development result if it has been provided in full for acceptance testing and is free from material defects and 
          defects of title, in particular if it fulfils the agreed acceptance criteria. Minor defects shall not entitle the customer to refuse acceptance. 
          Defects identified during the acceptance test shall be documented by the parties.
        </li>
        <li>
          The customer may declare acceptance expressly or by conclusive action. In particular, the development result shall also be deemed accepted if 
          the customer
          <ol class="text-justify list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
            <li>
              Uses the software to be created productively or with real data, unless the use serves exclusively for the acceptance test; or
            </li>
            <li>
              Has not refused acceptance within two (2) weeks of the complete provision of the development result for acceptance testing due to defects 
              that are not merely insignificant or has not declared justified reservations against the acceptability of the contractual services.
            </li>
          </ol>
          In all other respects, § 640 BGB applies.
        </li>
        <li>
          If provisional acceptance is carried out in a test environment, MBT will subsequently provide the Customer with the development results and a 
          password for activating the software for download. If provisional acceptance has not been agreed, the software will be made available immediately 
          after completion by sending a download link and a password to activate the software.
        </li>
        <li>
          The development result is created individually for the customer. MBT is only permitted to integrate third-party and open source software components 
          (hereinafter jointly referred to as ‘third-party components’) into the development result for the third-party components clearly specified in the order.
        </li>
        <li>
          Insofar as the creation of user documentation is owed, it should comprehensibly demonstrate essential functions of the software to be created for an 
          average user in accordance with the requirements specified in the order.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-2">2.4 General Provisions on the Provision of Services</h3>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          If MBT does not provide the development services within the agreed performance deadlines, it will be in default unless it is not responsible for the 
          delay. § Section 286 (1) BGB remains unaffected.
        </li>
        <li>
          MBT may, with the prior written consent of the Customer, use the support of third parties (‘subcontractors’) to fulfil the contract. MBT is 
          liable for the actions of a subcontractor in the same way as for its own actions.
        </li>
        <li>
          The place of fulfilment for all obligations arising from the commissioning of software development is the registered office of MBT.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-2">2.5 Customer’s Duty to Co-Operate</h3>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          The Customer must provide appropriate support for the successful production of the development result in each phase by actively 
          co-operating.
        </li>
        <li>
          In particular, the Customer will provide MBT with the information and data from the Customer’s sphere necessary for the proper 
          production of the development result in good time and, where necessary, allow MBT employees reasonable access to the Customer’s 
          business premises during the Customer’s business hours.
        </li>
        <li>
          If preliminary acceptance in a test environment has been agreed, the Customer will provide the test environment required for 
          acceptance. The test environment shall meet the requirements of the software to be tested in accordance with the order.
        </li>
        <li>
          If the customer does not provide the agreed co-operation services on time or not properly, the agreed service and installation dates 
          shall be postponed accordingly. The parties shall document the adjustment of the performance dates.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-2">2.6 Rights to the Development Result</h3>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          Upon final acceptance of the development result and full payment of the remuneration, the customer shall receive the irrevocable, 
          non-exclusive right to use the development results. The customer may load the software into the working memory of his systems and 
          use it as intended.
        </li>
        <li>
          The customer is also entitled to make a backup copy necessary to guarantee future use; he must label this as such and affix a copyright 
          notice. The customer is only authorised to reproduce and decompile the software under the conditions of §§ 69d Abs. 3, 69e UrhG.
        </li>
        <li>
          The customer is not authorised to rent out, sub-license, reproduce by wire or wireless means, make publicly accessible or make available 
          to third parties in any other way the development results. Third parties in this sense do not include employees in the customer’s 
          business operations and persons employed by the customer to ensure the intended use.
        </li>
        <li>
          The customer is entitled to permanently transfer the acquired copy of the development results to a third party, taking into account 
          the scope of the rights granted here. in this case, the customer undertakes to completely cease using the development results upon 
          conclusion of the contract and to delete all copies of the development results, unless he is obliged to retain them for a longer period. 
          MBT may request information from the customer on the implementation of the measures to be carried out in accordance with the preceding 
          sentence.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-2">2.7 Third-Party Components</h3>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          Insofar as the development result contains open source software components, the relevant open source licence conditions, which 
          are attached to the order, shall apply exclusively.
        </li>
        <li>
          These terms and conditions shall apply to other third-party components.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-2">2.8 Change Requests</h3>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          Until acceptance of the development result, the customer may request changes to the requirements for the development result in 
          writing at any time (hereinafter referred to as ‘change requests’). MBT may propose changes in writing.
        </li>
        <li>
          MBT will examine the Customer’s change requests within a reasonable period of time. Insofar as the examination of the change request 
          requires considerable effort on the part of MBT, MBT is entitled to reasonable reimbursement of expenses. MBT must first notify the 
          Customer in writing of the expenses incurred for the examination. The inspection will only be carried out if the Customer then agrees 
          to the inspection in writing.
        </li>
        <li>
          During the inspection, MBT will continue the services in accordance with the existing contract, unless the Customer requests an 
          interruption in text form. Agreed service deadlines will be extended by the duration of the requested interruption and by a reasonable 
          restart period.
        </li>
        <li>
          MBT will communicate the result of the examination of a change request in text form within a reasonable period of time, but in any case 
          within ten (10) working days of receipt of the change request. If the change request is feasible, MBT will offer to implement it on 
          reasonable terms.
        </li>
        <li>
          If the Customer maintains the change request after receipt of MBT’s offer, its implementation is thereby agreed.
        </li>
        <li>
          Agreed service changes must be documented by the parties in a suitable form as order changes.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-2">2.9 Remuneration and Terms of Payment</h3>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          MBT shall receive an expense-based remuneration from the Customer for the contractual production and transfer of the development result.
        </li>
        <li>
          The work incurred will be calculated on the basis of working hours. The hourly rate stated in the order shall apply.
        </li>
        <li>
          The time spent will be invoiced on a monthly basis. MBT will issue an invoice for this, stating the activity and the time spent.
        </li>
        <li>
          The remuneration covers in full all services provided by MBT for the contractual production and transfer of the development result and 
          the rights of use granted to the development result.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-2">2.10 Material Defects and Defects of Title</h3>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          MBT warrants that the development result is free from material defects and defects of title at the time of transfer of risk. Sections 634 
          et seq. BGB APPLY.
        </li>
        <li>
          Unless a different quality has been agreed, the development result must at least correspond to the recognised state of the art in science 
          and technology at the time of acceptance.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <!-- Section 3 -->
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6">
        3. Conditions for the Sale of Spare Parts
      </h2>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-2">3.1 Conclusion of Contract</h3>
      <p class="text-justify">
        A contract for the purchase of goods is only concluded when the Customer places an order and MBT accepts this offer, for example by confirming 
        the order in text form or by delivering the goods.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-2">3.2 Prices</h3>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          Unless otherwise agreed in individual cases, the current prices at the time of conclusion of the contract shall apply, ex warehouse, plus 
          statutory value added tax.
        </li>
        <li>
          In the case of sale to destination, the customer shall bear the agreed transport costs ex warehouse and the costs of any transport insurance 
          requested by the customer. Any customs duties, fees, taxes and other public charges shall be borne by the customer.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-2">3.3 Delivery Period and Delay in Delivery</h3>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          The delivery period is agreed individually or specified by MBT when the order is accepted. If this is not the case, the delivery period is 6 
          weeks from conclusion of the contract.
        </li>
        <li>
          If MBT fails to meet binding delivery deadlines for reasons for which it is not responsible (non-availability of the service), MBT will inform 
          the Customer of this immediately and at the same time notify the Customer of the expected new delivery deadline. If the service is still not 
          available within the new delivery period, MBT is entitled to withdraw from the contract in whole or in part; any consideration already paid by 
          the Customer will be refunded immediately. Non-availability of the service exists, for example, in the event of late delivery by a supplier, 
          if MBT has concluded a congruent hedging transaction, in the event of other disruptions in the supply chain, for example due to force majeure, 
          or if MBT is not obliged to procure in individual cases.
        </li>
        <li>
          The occurrence of default in delivery is determined in accordance with the statutory provisions. In any case, however, a reminder from the 
          Customer is required.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-2">3.4 Delivery, Transfer of Risk, Acceptance, Default of Acceptance</h3>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          Delivery shall be ex warehouse, which is also the place of fulfilment for the delivery and any subsequent fulfilment. At the customer’s request 
          and expense, the goods shall be dispatched to another destination (sale to destination). Unless otherwise agreed, MBT is entitled to determine 
          the type of dispatch (in particular transport company, dispatch route, packaging) itself.
        </li>
        <li>
          The risk of accidental loss and accidental deterioration of the goods is transferred to the Customer at the latest upon handover. In the case 
          of sale by dispatch, however, the risk of accidental loss and accidental deterioration of the goods as well as the risk of delay shall pass 
          to the customer upon delivery of the goods to the forwarding agent, carrier or other person or organisation designated to carry out the shipment.
        </li>
        <li>
          If the Customer is in default of acceptance, fails to co-operate or if MBT’s delivery is delayed for other reasons for which the Customer is 
          responsible, MBT is entitled to demand compensation for the resulting damage including additional expenses (e.g. storage costs).
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-2">3.5 Retention of Title</h3>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          Until full payment of all present and future claims of MBT arising from the purchase contract and an ongoing business relationship (secured claims), 
          MBT retains title to the goods sold.
        </li>
        <li>
          The goods subject to retention of title may not be pledged to third parties or assigned as security until the secured claims have been paid in full. The 
          Customer must inform MBT immediately in writing if an application is made to open insolvency proceedings or if third parties have access to the goods 
          belonging to MBT (e.g. seizures).
        </li>
        <li>
          In the event of breach of contract by the Customer, in particular non-payment of the purchase price due, MBT is entitled to withdraw from the contract 
          in accordance with the statutory provisions and/or to demand the return of the goods on the basis of the retention of title. The demand for the return 
          of the goods does not at the same time include a declaration of cancellation; MBT is rather entitled to demand only the return of the goods and to reserve 
          the right to cancel the contract. If the Customer does not pay the purchase price due, MBT may only assert these rights if MBT has previously set the 
          Customer a reasonable deadline for payment without success or if the setting of such a deadline is dispensable under the statutory provisions.
        </li>
        <li>
          The customer is authorised, until revoked in accordance with these terms and conditions, to resell and/or process the goods subject to retention of 
          title in the ordinary course of business. In this case, the following provisions shall apply in addition:
          <ol class="text-justify list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
            <li>
              The retention of title extends to the full value of the products created by processing, mixing or combining the goods of MBT, whereby MBT is deemed 
              to be the manufacturer. If, in the event of processing, mixing or combination with goods of third parties, their right of ownership remains, MBT 
              acquires co-ownership in proportion to the invoice values of the processed, mixed or combined goods. In all other respects, the same applies to the 
              resulting product as to the goods delivered subject to retention of title.
            </li>
            <li>
              The Customer hereby assigns to MBT as security the claims against third parties arising from the resale of the goods or the product in total or 
              in the amount of MBT’s possible co-ownership share in accordance with the above paragraph. MBT accepts the assignment. The above-mentioned obligations 
              of the Customer also apply with regard to the assigned claims.
            </li>
            <li>
              In addition to MBT, the Customer remains authorised to collect the claim. MBT undertakes not to collect the claim as long as the Customer fulfils 
              his payment obligations to MBT, there is no deficiency in his ability to pay and MBT does not assert the retention of title by exercising a right 
              under these terms and conditions. If this is the case, however, MBT may demand that the Customer informs MBT of the assigned claims and their 
              debtors, provides all information necessary for collection, hands over the relevant documents and informs the debtors (third parties) of the 
              assignment. In this case, MBT is also entitled to revoke the Customer’s authorisation to resell and process the goods subject to retention of title.
            </li>
            <li>
              If the realisable value of the securities exceeds MBT’s claims by more than 10%, MBT will release securities of its own choice at the Customer’s 
              request.
            </li>
          </ol>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-2">3.6 Warranty Claims</h3>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          The statutory provisions shall apply to the customer’s warranty rights in the event of material defects and defects of title (including incorrect 
          and short delivery as well as improper assembly/installation or defective instructions), unless otherwise specified below.
        </li>
        <li>
          The basis for liability for defects is above all the agreement reached on the quality and intended use of the goods (including accessories and 
          instructions). All product descriptions and manufacturer’s specifications which are the subject of the individual contract or which were made 
          public by MBT (in particular in catalogues or on MBT’s Internet homepage) at the time the contract was concluded are deemed to be an agreement on 
          quality in this sense.
        </li>
        <li>
          In the case of goods with digital elements or other digital content, MBT is only obliged to provide and, where applicable, update the digital 
          content insofar as this expressly results from a quality agreement in accordance with the preceding paragraph. MBT accepts no liability in this 
          respect for public statements made by the manufacturer or other third parties
        </li>
        <li>
          MBT is generally not liable for defects that the Customer is aware of or is grossly negligent in not being aware of when the contract is concluded 
          (Section 442 BGB). Furthermore, the Customer’s claims for defects presuppose that he has fulfilled his statutory duties of inspection and 
          notification (§§ 377, 381 HGB). If a defect becomes apparent upon delivery, inspection or at any later point in time, MBT must be notified of this 
          in writing without delay. In any case, obvious defects must be reported in writing within 3 working days of delivery and defects not recognisable 
          during the inspection within the same period from discovery. If the Customer fails to carry out the proper inspection and/or report defects, MBT’s 
          liability for the defect not reported or not reported in good time or not reported properly is excluded in accordance with the statutory provisions. 
          In the case of goods intended for fitting, mounting or installation, this also applies if the defect only becomes apparent after the corresponding 
          processing as a result of a breach of one of these obligations; in this case, the Customer is in particular not entitled to claim compensation for 
          corresponding costs such as removal and installation costs.
        </li>
        <li>
          If the delivered item is defective, MBT may initially choose whether to provide subsequent fulfilment by remedying the defect (rectification) or 
          by delivering a defect-free item (replacement delivery). If the type of subsequent fulfilment chosen by MBT is unreasonable for the Customer in an 
          individual case, the Customer may reject it. MBT’s right to refuse subsequent fulfilment under the statutory conditions remains unaffected. 
        </li>
        <li>
          MBT is entitled to make the subsequent fulfilment owed dependent on the Customer paying the purchase price due. However, the Customer is entitled 
          to retain a reasonable proportion of the purchase price in relation to the defect.
        </li>
        <li>
          If a reasonable deadline to be set by the customer for subsequent fulfilment has expired unsuccessfully or is dispensable in accordance with the 
          statutory provisions, the customer may withdraw from the purchase contract or reduce the purchase price in accordance with the statutory provisions. 
          In the case of an insignificant defect, however, there is no right of cancellation.
        </li>
        <li>
          Claims of the customer for reimbursement of expenses in accordance with § 445a Abs. 1 BGB are excluded, unless the last contract in the supply 
          chain is a consumer goods purchase (§§ 478, 474 BGB) or a consumer contract for the provision of digital products (§§ 445c S. 2, 327 Abs. 5, 327u BGB). 
          The customer’s claims for damages or reimbursement of futile expenses (§ 284 BGB) shall only exist in accordance with the conditions, even in 
          the event of defects in the goods.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <!-- Section 4 -->
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6">4. Terms of Payment</h2>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          The purchase price for goods is due and payable within 14 days of invoicing and delivery of the goods. However, MBT is entitled at any 
          time, even within the framework of an ongoing business relationship, to make a delivery in whole or in part only against advance payment. 
          MBT will declare a corresponding reservation with the order confirmation.
        </li>
        <li>
          Payment for software development services is due within 14 days of invoicing.
        </li>
        <li>
          Upon expiry of the above payment deadlines, the Customer will be in default. Interest will be charged on the purchase price or remuneration 
          payable during the period of default at the applicable statutory default interest rate. MBT reserves the right to claim further damages for 
          default. MBT’s claim to commercial maturity interest (Section 353 HGB) against merchants remains unaffected.
        </li>
        <li>
          The Customer is only entitled to rights of set-off or retention insofar as his claim has been legally established or is undisputed. In the 
          event of defects in the service, the customer’s counter-rights shall remain unaffected.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <!-- Section 5 -->
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6">5. Statutory Limitation</h2>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          Notwithstanding § 438 Abs. 1 Nr. 3 BGB and § 634a Abs. 1 Nr. 1 and Nr. 3, the general limitation period for claims arising from material 
          defects and defects of title shall be one year from delivery or acceptance.
        </li>
        <li>
          The above limitation periods of the law on sales and contracts for work and labour shall also apply to contractual and non-contractual 
          claims for damages of the customer based on a defect of the goods, unless the application of the regular statutory limitation period 
          (§§ 195, 199 BGB) would lead to a shorter limitation period in individual cases.
        <li>
          In the event of unlimited liability in accordance with the following condition, the statutory limitation periods shall apply.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <!-- Section 6 -->
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6">6. Liability</h2>
      <ol class="text-justify list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 marker:font-semibold">
        <li>
          Apart from liability for material defects and defects of title, MBT is liable without limitation insofar as the cause of the damage is based on 
          intent or gross negligence.
        </li>
        <li>
          MBT is also liable for the slightly negligent breach of material obligations (obligations whose breach jeopardises the achievement of the purpose 
          of the contract) and for the breach of cardinal obligations (obligations whose fulfilment is essential for the proper performance of the contract 
          and on whose compliance the Customer regularly relies), but in each case only for foreseeable damage typical of the contract. MBT is not liable for 
          the slightly negligent breach of obligations other than the above obligations.
        </li>
        <li>
          The limitations of liability in the above paragraph do not apply in the event of injury to life, limb or health, for a defect following the 
          assumption of a guarantee for the quality of the product and in the event of fraudulently concealed defects. Liability under the Product Liability 
          Act remains unaffected.
        </li>
        <li>
          If the liability of MBT is excluded or limited, this also applies to the personal liability of its employees, representatives and vicarious agents.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>

  </section>
</BaseLayout>